    <div class="container">
      <article class="blog-article">

        <div class="blog-meta">
          <span>📍 Written for Sandy &amp; Salt Lake County homeowners</span>
          <span>⏱ 4 min read</span>
        </div>

        <p>
          A storm rolled through last night. Maybe you heard it — hail hitting the windows,
          wind picking up across the Wasatch Front. Now you're standing in your driveway
          wondering if your roof took a hit. Most homeowners in Sandy and the surrounding
          area have no idea what storm damage actually looks like until it shows up as a
          leak months later. By then, the insurance window has closed and you're paying
          out of pocket. This guide walks you through what to check — and when to call.
        </p>

        <h2>Start from the Ground — Don't Get on the Roof Yourself</h2>
        <p>
          Before you pull out a ladder, do a slow walk around the perimeter of your house
          with your eyes up. You won't catch everything from ground level, but you can
          spot the obvious: missing shingles, shifted ridge caps, debris resting on the
          roof, or sections where the surface looks different from the rest. Look for
          shingles that are curled at the edges, completely gone, or sitting in your yard.
          If you see any of those — stop. You've already seen enough to call for an inspection.
        </p>

        <h2>What Hail Damage Actually Looks Like</h2>
        <p>
          This is where homeowners get it wrong. Hail damage doesn't look like a hole.
          It looks like a bruise. Up close, you'll see circular soft spots on the shingles
          where the granule coating has been knocked loose. The surface looks darker or
          slightly shinier in those spots. You might also see small dents in metal
          flashing, gutters, or your AC unit — those are actually reliable indicators,
          because metal reads hail impact clearly while shingles require a trained eye.
        </p>
        <p>
          The sign most homeowners overlook: granules in the gutters. After a hail event,
          granule coating washes off damaged shingles and collects in your gutters and
          downspouts. If you clean your gutters and see what looks like coarse black sand,
          that's your roof losing its protective layer. It won't leak today — but it'll
          leak sooner than it should.
        </p>

        <h2>What Wind Damage Looks Like</h2>
        <p>
          Wind damage shows up differently. Walk the perimeter again and look for shingles
          that are lifted at the corners — they'll catch light differently than flat ones.
          Missing shingles are obvious. Less obvious: check the flashing around your
          chimney, skylights, and any spot where the roof meets a vertical wall. Wind gets
          under those edges and pulls them loose.
        </p>
        <p>
          Pay special attention to the ridge cap — the strip of shingles running along the
          very peak of the roof. It takes the most wind exposure and tends to lift first.
          If even one ridge cap shingle is gone or shifted, water has a direct path in.
        </p>

        <h2>Check the Gutters and Downspouts</h2>
        <p>
          While you're outside, pull the downspout extension away from the house and look
          at what's been collecting. Granules are a red flag. So is standing water or
          debris backed up at the gutter seams — that can point to flashing problems
          where the gutter meets the fascia board.
        </p>
        <p>
          If you have gutters with guards, check that the guards themselves aren't dented
          or shifted. Damaged gutter guards after a storm are a solid indicator that the
          roof above took the same hit.
        </p>

        <h2>Get Into the Attic</h2>
        <p>
          If you can safely access your attic, go up after a storm with a flashlight.
          You're looking for water stains on the decking (the wood sheeting under the
          shingles), soft spots in the wood, or anywhere daylight is visible through
          the roof. You don't need to see active dripping — old staining tells you water
          has gotten in at some point, and recent staining tells you it happened during
          last night's storm.
        </p>

        <h2>Call Before You File — This Is the Part That Matters</h2>
        <p>
          Here's the mistake most homeowners make: they see something, they call their
          insurance company first, an adjuster comes out, and without independent
          documentation from a roofer, the claim gets lowballed or denied. Adjusters
          work for the insurance company. Their job is to close the claim, not maximize
          your settlement.
        </p>
        <p>
          Get a licensed roofer out first. They'll document everything — photos,
          measurements, a written damage report — before your adjuster visit. That
          documentation is your leverage. It's also what protects you if you need to
          dispute a denial later.
        </p>

